There are several rules; pick one set and be consistent.

A lot of technical or learned writing does not do the capitalization
thing for titles or headings, capitalizing only the first word and
proper nouns.  The same way that capitalization is done in ordinary
running text.

The method common to books and magazine articles for popular
consumption is called &quot;headline style.&quot;
1. Capitalize the first word, as one would for a sentence.
2. Do not capitalize the articles (a, an, the).
3. Do not capitalize short prepositions (on, off, in...four letters or
fewer).  Long prepositions are usually capitalized (around, through...
six letters or more).  Yes, that leaves prepositions having five
letters out; &quot;about&quot; is capitalized by some and not capitalized by
others.

An Introduction to Applied Linguistics (if mentioned in running text:
italicized if that is the title of the book; in quotation marks if
that is the title of an article in a magazine or journal or the title
of a chapter in a book) would be very common.

An introduction to applied linguistics would not be unusual in a
journal (&quot;journal&quot; meaning a magazine that has articles of interest to
scholars of a particular field, a magazine for specialists) as the
title of the article, or in running text in an article that refers to
the book or article that has that title.

An Introduction To Applied Linguistics is incorrect.

Cece
