In Denmark we have a certain &quot;office&quot; which controll how the
language is used and which publish dictionaries about the
correct way of spelling Danish. I don't think you have a
similar institution in England or in the USA. This may lead to
some different opinions about what is correct English and what
is not.

You'll probably remember a heatedly discussion between some
English native speakers and one American native speaker, both
claiming that you could /could not say this sentence in
English:

He must have been being interviewed.

The English claimed that this was grammatical and the American
said that it was ungrammatical.

It is therefore very difficult to tell who is right when
talking about English grammar and conventions.

What I just wanted was to find out whether the definite
articles and the prepositions in general were written with
capitals in headlines, which I have seen several times, and
which are not - and when.

I have a book with the title: &quot;Foreign Language Acquistition
Research and the Classroom&quot;

Here I can see that all the words are written with capital
letters except for the conjunction and the definite article.

What I wanted to understand was /when/ or /if/ these
observations were general in headlines.

I am satisfied with the rules I have learned, but I am aware
of the fact that the rule differ sometimes, and a certain
conventional canon might not exist.

It is´interesting, however, that the headline :

&quot;Foreign Language Acquisition Research And The Classroom&quot; is
not correct, so some conventions or rules still prevail in my
way of thinking.

On the other hand it might also be wrong! :-0

The opinion that conjunctions, definte/indefinite articles and
some prepositions with letters less than or equal with 4
letters do not demand capital letters, and that prepositions
with 5 or more letters usually demands capitals - but words as
e.g. about can be used with both capital letter and without in
a headline.
