There are lots of style manuals online.

The APA style manual is, I think, the one from the American
Psychological Association.  Unless it's the one of similar name that
is used by newspapers; newspapers do not use italic type and
streamline typesetting in other ways too. http://apastyle.apa.org/

One of the most revered is the Chicago Manual of Style, which was
originally the house style of some company or other.  It is online
here: http://www.chicagomanualofstyle.org/home.html

Another of the most revered is the MLA Formatting and Style Guide.  I
don't know why people think highly of it, unless the bits of it I have
been told are the informants' misunderstandings.  Here it is:
http://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/557/01/

Then there is Strunk &amp; White, but I don't find a current edition
online, only the original 1918 edition.

Yes, we can answer questions of this type.  But be careful with the
answers!

Cece
